snippet.textDisplay: I blame Kathleen Kennedy and Rian Johnson for the mess.  JJ set up a lot of good ideas in TFA.  Ben killing Han could have should have been so much more.  Luke getting the light saber back should have been so much more.  Hux should have been so much more.  Rey being the daughter of Palpatine should have been so much more.  If anything had been continued and hinted at in TLJ, it could have been a decent trilogy.  Right now, it feels like Episode 7 and 9 are one story and 8 is the bastard step child that is ignored.  8 should have been the connective tissue, it should have set up things for pay off in 9.  8 is the reason 9 is so bad, they spent the entire movie trying to fix the massive shitshow that they didn't have time to tell their own story.

snippet.textDisplay:
i'm one of the very small minority of people who never liked the movies. the OG trilogy which is worshiped to this day was always boring as hell. the movies weren't bad, but they were just boring. my parents were huge SW fans so i grew up watching it, i watched the OG trology like 3 times in my childhood. i didn't even know about the trilogies until my mid teens, when i found out my chance because my parents had hated them so much they had basically hidden them away from the whole family. (i haven't seen any of those though, except for the last one). but the one thing that is appealing in the entire SW universe is clone wars. i have said this a million times to my family, but i have always said tv>>>>movies. because with movies, no matter how good or bad it is, it has to wrap up in around 2hrs (3, like endgame but really who movies are like that besides plays or movies based off of them). clone wars had 7 whole years to develop characters, environments, hell even animation that the audience could appreciate. it had REAL worldbuilding, and yes, it was original like the OG trology, but it was actually interesting. (not only that, the creator was actually a hardcore fan, like feige with MCU)


except for rogue one (and i would even include that to a degree), every single one of the post OG movies are just pathetic leeches of the original. it's like somehow, no matter what, lucas' spirit is in the production studio and is threatening to kill everyone's family if they don't reference to every single thing in the OG. it's obnoxious and grating, and i remember when i saw the last jedi i CRINGED every time the "da, da, da da da DAAAAA da" theme was used. and it didn't stop. it was used again and again in the movies. and that's just ONE leech. i'm not a star wars fan, i'm just a clone wars fan, and clone wars is so unlike star wars that it's really a product on its own thing. but i do know what it's like to be a diehard fan and be disappointed. and i'm sorry for everyone who wanted to love SW again, who were in their right to expect it to be better since the crew and cast should have done their best to be nothing like the prequels, still fresh in everyone's minds.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here's how I'd make the films. Have the knights of ren be the main
villains instead of Palpatine or Snoke or even have the first order.
Luke has his Jedi order and Leia is a jedi teacher. Leia has a cyan
lightsaber and Luke still has his green one. Rey is a scavenger and
found that she showed a little force potential when Luke found her
trying to find students. Finn was part of an experiment to create force
sensitive stormtroopers and was very young but the experiment fell after
the empire fell. The knights are Vader fanatics seeking out sith
holocrons that Vader left for a sinister purpose. Kylo has a green
crossguard as the green crystal was gifted by Luke but was cracked when
he damaged it in a fit of rage. I'd remove the bleeding crystal method
as I find it unique if a dark sider has a non red blade and a light
sider has a red blade. Rey has a double bladed purple lightsaber she
constructs, and Finn has a standard blue one. Rey unlike in the movies
we have seen, actually works hard and while she is talented she does
actually get trained before she does the cool stuff. The knights also
have red armored troopers similar to sith troopers as just body guards
as well. Along the way to defeat them, they come across other force
orders that are light sided, dark sided and even gray sided like the
guardians of the breath and imperial knights and they all have their own
agenda and beliefs.


Kylo does reform over time. Rey and Finn fall in love. Also it turns out
that with all the warring factions, a sith lord named Jar Jar was
behind everything as Jar Jar was a partner of Palpatine. Since Palpatine
had an apprentice, Jar Jar laid low hence his absence in later movies
until Palpatine was destroyed and JarJar would continue the rule of two
sith, trying to find other force users to corrupt like Rey. Rey turns
out to be Anakin Skywalker reincarnated. Anakin foresaw a sith lord in
the future and other dark siders and so Anakin gave up immortality to
reincarnate into another body. Hence why she has connections with Luke,
Leia and Kylo and also why Anakin is absent as a ghost and also explains
Rey's power. We'd see scenes of Rey interacting with her previous
incarnation Anakin. Turns out Jar Jar was behind the clone wars, the
empire and the warring factions between other force orders for a
sinister purpose as well and it comes down to Rey and Finn and Kylo
fighting against him, in his throne that looks similar to Palpatine's in
TROS. Jar Jar shoots red force lightning and has a dark core unstable
red lightsaber blade. Rey defeats him and the prophecy his fulfilled
when other dark siders are destroyed and when she destroys the last of
the sith as she is the chosen one reincarnated. What do you think? I
think this would be better than what we got.

snippet.textDisplay:
You sound like the guy that was talking behind me the entire movie after explicitly arriving late to the showing with his friends, intermittently kicking my seat as he pompously ranted and made not-funny jokes trying to make standard his cynical and pessimistic hatred of Star Wars. Videos like this on the new trilogy act like the OT was winning Oscars on its screenplay, because it was "CAMPBELLIAN", with the hero's journey being taught in english classes across America...but what it really was was a groundbreaking blockbuster praised for it's iconic acheivements in cinematography, sound design and post-production with the most expansive science-fiction world-building ever put to screen. People just jerked themselves off because of the Vader reveal-- a trope that was specific to one point in time-- one that kills the rewatchability.


I think people that aren't cunts about Star Wars enjoyed this trilogy because they accept the Star Wars films for the imaginative schlock they are and always have been. Fact of the matter is, these films are the best Star Wars has ever looked and sounded. The Force, the most criminally underdeveloped aspect of the franchise across the films, is actually shown off consistently, explored more than ever before--but even still, it's still retarded. If you take The Matrix for example, when Neo becomes the One, we SEE what he's manipulating. We SEE the code of the Matrix. We KNOW this is a computer. We become invested in the power fantasy. We understand the rules, we commit ourselves to them, we understand that it's going to take the acclamation of power by the protagonists to overcome the totalitarian regime.


The Force on the other hand, amongst other aspects of the Star Wars films, is trite and shallow. It immediately demands a suspension of disbelief, likely because the significance of the world, its physics and the development of its characters, was neither ever accounted for, and more likely, never the point. The point was only ever glory, style, spectacle, and immersion, of which I felt these films had tons of.


I mean, you say, why could Palpatine shoot mile-long force lightning, and I say, why the fuck is there a First Order, where'd they get the resources, why is morality so polarized in the Star Wars universe, why isn't force usage as democratized throughout the star wars universe the way magic is throughout the Harry Potter universe, why isn't it a fundamental constitutent of the galactic economy, what are the combative advantages of lightsabers, and if they truly exist, why aren't they a standard across the universe? Why aren't more people getting killed in these movies?


Idk man. I've lived with Star Wars my entire life, and it's only ever been a shitty story. Even with the """Legendary""" Clone Wars TV show. It's a goddamn western Shonen power fantasy-- and admit it or not, Rise of Skywalker was the most OD that power fantasy has literally ever been. So, to me, this video is 14 minutes of an entitled idiot who never got the point. You want some sci-fi that'll change your life, really make you think? Why in the fuck are you watching Star Wars?

snippet.textDisplay:
I love Prequels, and I also understand the hate for it.

But I just don’t understand the positive reception of The Force Awakens. I had to watch it three times in the cinema to convince myself, but my anger got worse and worse.

I’m glad that people finally opened their eyes. JJ is a terrible director/writer. How else would you continue his direction apart from going way off course like RJ did.

Star Wars Trilogy Saga is dead. Best to leave it that way.

snippet.textDisplay: I’m Going to compliment the Prequels. This isn’t to say that the second trilogy was good, or even better then the Disney trilogy, but I’ll say this. The prequels as a whole, were more cohesive, riskier, more innovative, and  I’ll argue more patient then the Disney trilogy. I’ll give gorge credit, he took risks with the second trilogy; contrast this with new films were the only film that tried out do something new, that being The Last Jedi, still feels constricted by its inclusion in the trilogy.
